za M(4), Srivastava \n50: AK(4), Kim EY(3), Zalk R(5), Shahar A(5), Cohen-Schwartz S(6), Meyron-Holtz \n51: EG(7), Bou-Abdallah F(4), Mancias JD(8)(9), Frank GA(10)(11)(12).\n52: \n53: Author information:\n54: (1)The Kreitman School of Advanced Graduate Studies, Marcus Family Campus, \n55: Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, Beer-Sheva, Israel.\n56: (2)Department of Life Sciences, Marcus Family Campus, Ben-Gurion University of \n57: the Negev, Beer-Sheva, Israel.\n58: (3)Division of Radiation and Genome Stability, Department of Radiation Oncology, \n59: Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA.\n60: (4)Department of Chemistry, State University of New York at Potsdam (SUNY \n61: Potsdam), Potsdam, NY, USA.\n62: (5)Ilse Katz Institute for Nanoscale Science & Technology, Marcus Family Campus, \n63: Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, Beer-Sheva, Israel.\n64: (6)The National Institute for Biotechnology in the Negev - NIBN, Marcus Family \n65: Campus, Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, Beer-Sheva, Israel.\n66: (7)Faculty of Biotechnology and Food Engineering, Technion, Haifa, Israel.\n67: (8)Division of Radiation and Genome Stability, Department of Radiation Oncology, \n68: Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Harvard Medical School, Boston, MA, USA. \n69: Joseph_Mancias@dfci.harvard.edu.\n70: (9)Department of Radiation Oncology, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Harvard \n71: Medical School, Boston, MA, USA. Joseph_Mancias@dfci.harvard.edu.\n72: (10)Department of Life Sciences, Marcus Family Campus, Ben-Gurion University of \n73: the Negev, Beer-Sheva, Israel. frankg@bgu.ac.il.\n74: (11)Ilse Katz Institute for Nanoscale Science & Technology, Marcus Family \n75: Campus, Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, Beer-Sheva, Israel. \n76: frankg@bgu.ac.il.\n77: (12)The National Institute for Biotechnology in the Negev - NIBN, Marcus Family \n78: Campus, Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, Beer-Sheva, Israel. \n79: frankg@bgu.ac.il.\n80: (#)Contributed equally\n81: \n82: The interaction between nuclear receptor coactivator 4 (NCOA4) and the iron \n83: storage protein ferritin is a crucial component of cellular iron homeostasis. \n84: The binding of NCOA4 to the FTH1 subunits of ferritin initiates ferritinophagy-a \n85: ferritin-specific autophagic pathway leading to the release of the iron stored \n86: inside ferritin. The dysregulation of NCOA4 is associated with several diseases, \n87: including neurodegenerative disorders and cancer, highlighting the \n88: NCOA4-ferritin interface as a prime target for drug development. Here, we \n89: present the cryo-EM structure of the NCOA4-FTH1 interface, resolving 16 amino \n90: acids of NCOA4 that are crucial for the interaction. The characterization of \n91: mutants, designed to modulate the NCOA4-FTH1 interaction, is used to validate \n92: the significance of the different features of the binding site. Our results \n93: explain the role of the large solvent-exposed hydrophobic patch found on the \n94: surface of FTH1 and pave the way for the rational development of ferritinophagy \n95: modulators.\n96: \n97: © 2024. The Author(s).\n98: \n99: DOI: 10.1038/s41467-024-48151-1\n100: PMCID: PMC11076521\n101: PMID: 38714719 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n102: \n103: Conflict of interest statement: GAF and JDM hold the pending provisional patent \n104: application 63/534,363 for modulating ferritinophagy based on the structure and \n105: mutants described in this paper. JDM reports research support from Novartis and \n106: Casma Therapeutics and has consulted for Third Rock Ventures and Skyhawk \n107: Therapeutics, all unrelated to the submitted work. All other authors declare no \n108: conflict of interest.\n\n(End of file - total 108 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:38714719\ntitle: Structural basis for the intracellular regulation of ferritin degradation.\nauthors:\n- Hoelzgen F\n- Nguyen TTP\n- Klukin E\n- Boumaiza M\n- Srivastava AK\n- Kim EY\n- Zalk R\n- Shahar A\n- Cohen-Schwartz S\n- Meyron-Holtz EG\n- Bou-Abdallah F\n- Mancias JD\n- Frank GA\njournal: Nat Commun\nyear: '2024'\ndoi: 10.1038/s41467-024-48151-1","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_38714719.md","time":{"start":1778983329122,"end":1778983329164}},"id":"prt_e33ab5d5d0019oAbsU6cVv4gyd","sessionID":"ses_1cc5be10bffeihXrzY1FV2TH0l","messageID":"msg_e33ab468a001sFrzEbbjcLiKez"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778983329188,"sessionID":"ses_1cc5be10bffeihXrzY1FV2TH0l","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_kJbWAogVl8xilhVANT9nSm6n","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_25327288.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_25327288.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:25327288\n3: title: Selective VPS34 inhibitor blocks autophagy and uncovers a role for NCOA4 in ferritin degradation and iron homeostasis in vivo.\n4: authors:\n5: - Dowdle WE\n6: - Nyfeler B\n7: - Nagel J\n8: - Elling RA\n9: - Liu S\n10: - Triantafellow E\n11: - Menon S\n12: - Wang Z\n13: - Honda A\n14: - Pardee G\n15: - Cantwell J\n16: - Luu C\n17: - Cornella-Taracido I\n18: - Harrington E\n19: - Fekkes P\n20: - Lei H\n21: - Fang Q\n22: - Digan ME\n23: - Burdick D\n24: - Powers AF\n25: - Helliwell SB\n26: - \"D'Aquin S\"\n27: - Bastien J\n28: - Wang H\n29: - Wiederschain D\n30: - Kuerth J\n31: - Bergman P\n32: - Schwalb D\n33: - Thomas J\n34: - Ugwonali S\n35: - Harbinski F\n36: - Tallarico J\n37: - Wilson CJ\n38: - Myer VE\n39: - Porter JA\n40: - Bussiere DE\n41: - Finan PM\n42: - Labow MA\n43: - Mao X\n44: - Hamann LG\n45: - Manning BD\n46: - Valdez RA\n47: - Nicholson T\n48: - Schirle M\n49: - Knapp MS\n50: - Keaney EP\n51: - Murphy LO\n52: journal: Nat Cell Biol\n53: year: '2014'\n54: doi: 10.1038/ncb3053\n55: keywords:\n56: - Animals\n57: - \"Autophagy/drug effects, physiology\"\n58: - \"Cells, Cultured\"\n59: - \"Class III Phosphatidylinositol 3-Kinases/antagonists & inhibitors\"\n60: - Ferritins/metabolism\n61: - Homeostasis/physiology\n62: - Humans\n63: - Iron/metabolism\n64: - Lysosomes/metabolism\n65: - Mice\n66: - Nuclear Receptor Coactivators/metabolism\n67: - Phagosomes/metabolism\n68: - Protein Binding\n69: content_type: abstract_only\n70: ---\n71: \n72: # Selective VPS34 inhibitor blocks autophagy and uncovers a role for NCOA4 in ferritin degradation and iron homeostasis in vivo.\n73: **Authors:** Dowdle WE, Nyfeler B, Nagel J, Elling RA, Liu S, Triantafellow E, Menon S, Wang Z, Honda A, Pardee G, Cantwell J, Luu C, Cornella-Taracido I, Harrington E, Fekkes P, Lei H, Fang Q, Digan ME, Burdick D, Powers AF, Helliwell SB, D'Aquin S, Bastien J, Wang H, Wiederschain D, Kuerth J, Bergman P, Schwalb D, Thomas J, Ugwonali S, Harbinski F, Tallarico J, Wilson CJ, Myer VE, Porter JA, Bussiere DE, Finan PM, Labow MA, Mao X, Hamann LG, Manning BD, Valdez RA, Nicholson T, Schirle M, Knapp MS, Keaney EP, Murphy LO\n74: **Journal:** Nat Cell Biol (2014)\n75: **DOI:** [10.1038/ncb3053](https://doi.org/10.1038/ncb3053)\n76: \n77: ## Content\n78: \n79: 1. Nat Cell Biol. 2014 Nov;16(11):1069-79. doi: 10.1038/ncb3053. Epub 2014 Oct\n80: 19.\n81: \n82: Selective VPS34 inhibitor blocks autophagy and uncovers a role for NCOA4 in \n83: ferritin degradation and iron homeostasis in vivo.\n84: \n85: Dowdle WE(1), Nyfeler B(2), Nagel J(1), Elling RA(3), Liu S(1), Triantafellow \n86: E(1), Menon S(1), Wang Z(1), Honda A(1), Pardee G(3), Cantwell J(3), Luu C(3), \n87: Cornella-Taracido I(1), Harrington E(1), Fekkes P(1), Lei H(1), Fang Q(1), Digan \n88: ME(1), Burdick D(1), Powers AF(1), Helliwell SB(2), D'Aquin S(2), Bastien J(2), \n89: Wang H(1), Wiederschain D(1), Kuerth J(1), Bergman P(1), Schwalb D(1), Thomas \n90: J(1), Ugwonali S(1), Harbinski F(1), Tallarico J(1), Wilson CJ(1), Myer VE(1), \n91: Porter JA(1), Bussiere DE(3), Finan PM(1), Labow MA(1), Mao X(1), Hamann LG(1), \n92: Manning BD(4), Valdez RA(1), Nicholson T(1), Schirle M(1), Knapp MS(3), Keaney \n93: EP(1), Murphy LO(1).\n94: \n95: Author information:\n96: (1)Novartis Institutes for BioMedical Research, 250 Massachusetts Avenue, \n97: Cambridge, Massachusetts 02139, USA.\n98: (2)Novartis Institutes for BioMedical Research, Novartis Campus, CH-4056 Basel, \n99: Switzerland.\n100: (3)Novartis Institutes for BioMedical Research, 4560 Horton Street Emeryville, \n101: California 94608, USA.\n102: (4)Department of Genetics and Complex Diseases, Harvard School of Public Health, \n103: 665 Huntington Avenue, Boston, Massachusetts 02115, USA.\n104: \n105: Cells rely on autophagy to clear misfolded proteins and damaged organelles to \n106: maintain cellular homeostasis. In this study we use the new autophagy inhibitor \n107: PIK-III to screen for autophagy substrates. PIK-III is a selective inhibitor of \n108: VPS34 that binds a unique hydrophobic pocket not present in related kinases such \n109: as PI(3)Kα. PIK-III acutely inhibits autophagy and de novo lipidation of LC3, \n110: and leads to the stabilization of autophagy substrates. By performing \n111: ubiquitin-affinity proteomics on PIK-III-treated cells we identified substrates \n112: including NCOA4, which accumulates in ATG7-deficient cells and co-localizes with \n113: autolysosomes. NCOA4 directly binds ferritin heavy chain-1 (FTH1) to target the \n114: iron-binding ferritin complex with a relative molecular mass of 450,000 to \n115: autolysosomes following starvation or iron depletion. Interestingly, Ncoa4(-/-) \n116: mice exhibit a profound accumulation of iron in splenic macrophages, which are \n117: critical for the reutilization of iron from engulfed red blood cells. Taken \n118: together, the results of this study provide a new mechanism for selective \n119: autophagy of ferritin and reveal a previously unappreciated role for autophagy \n120: and NCOA4 in the control of iron homeostasis in vivo.\n121: \n122: DOI: 10.1038/ncb3053\n123: PMID: 25327288 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 123 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:25327288\ntitle: Selective VPS34 inhibitor blocks autophagy and uncovers a role for NCOA4 in ferritin degradation and iron homeostasis in vivo.\nauthors:\n- Dowdle WE\n- Nyfeler B\n- Nagel J\n- Elling RA\n- Liu S\n- Triantafellow E\n- Menon S\n- Wang Z\n- Honda A\n- Pardee G\n- Cantwell J\n- Luu C\n- Cornella-Taracido I\n- Harrington E\n- Fekkes P\n- Lei H","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_25327288.md","time":{"start":1778983329130,"end":1778983329169}},"id":"prt_e33ab5d650016x8iP1JKWMry7Q","sessionID":"ses_1cc5be10bffeihXrzY1FV2TH0l","messageID":"msg_e33ab468a001sFrzEbbjcLiKez"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778983329188,"sessionID":"ses_1cc5be10bffeihXrzY1FV2TH0l","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_mhMXxhV6EiZA7X8H2tw0mFFZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_26436293.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_26436293.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:26436293\n3: title: Ferritinophagy via NCOA4 is required for erythropoiesis and is regulated by iron dependent HERC2-mediated proteolysis.\n4: authors:\n5: - Mancias JD\n6: - Pontano Vaites L\n7: - Nissim S\n8: - Biancur DE\n9: - Kim AJ\n10: - Wang X\n11: - Liu Y\n12: - Goessling W\n13: - Kimmelman AC\n14: - Harper JW\n15: journal: Elife\n16: year: '2015'\n17: doi: 10.7554/eLife.10308\n18: keywords:\n19: - Animals\n20: - Autophagy\n21: - Cell Line\n22: - Erythropoiesis\n23: - Ferritins/metabolism\n24: - Guanine Nucleotide Exchange Factors/metabolism\n25: - Humans\n26: - Iron/metabolism\n27: - Lysosomes/metabolism\n28: - Nuclear Receptor Coactivators/metabolism\n29: - Oxidoreductases\n30: - Phagosomes/metabolism\n31: - Proteolysis\n32: - Ubiquitin-Protein Ligases\n33: - Zebrafish\n34: content_type: abstract_only\n35: ---\n36: \n37: # Ferritinophagy via NCOA4 is required for erythropoiesis and is regulated by iron dependent HERC2-mediated proteolysis.\n38: **Authors:** Mancias JD, Pontano Vaites L, Nissim S, Biancur DE, Kim AJ, Wang X, Liu Y, Goessling W, Kimmelman AC, Harper JW\n39: **Journal:** Elife (2015)\n40: **DOI:** [10.7554/eLife.10308](https://doi.org/10.7554/eLife.10308)\n41: \n42: ## Content\n43: \n44: 1. Elife. 2015 Oct 5;4:e10308. doi: 10.7554/eLife.10308.\n45: \n46: Ferritinophagy via NCOA4 is required for erythropoiesis and is regulated by iron \n47: dependent HERC2-mediated proteolysis.\n48: \n49: Mancias JD(1)(2)(3), Pontano Vaites L(1), Nissim S(4)(5)(6), Biancur DE(2), Kim \n50: AJ(4), Wang X(2), Liu Y(1), Goessling W(4)(5)(6)(7)(8), Kimmelman AC(2), Harper \n51: JW(1).\n52: \n53: Author information:\n54: (1)Department of Cell Biology, Harvard Medical School, Boston, United States.\n55: (2)Division of Genomic Stability and DNA Repair, Department of Radiation \n56: Oncology, Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Boston, United States.\n57: (3)Department of Radiation Oncology, Harvard Medical School, Boston, United \n58: States.\n59: (4)Gastroenterology Division, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Harvard Medical \n60: School, Boston, United States.\n61: (5)Genetics Division, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Boston, United States.\n62: (6)Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, Boston, United States.\n63: (7)Harvard Stem Cell Institute, Cambridge, United States.\n64: (8)Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard, Cambridge, United States.\n65: \n66: NCOA4 is a selective cargo receptor for the autophagic turnover of ferritin, a \n67: process critical for regulation of intracellular iron bioavailability. However, \n68: how ferritinophagy flux is controlled and the roles of NCOA4 in iron-dependent \n69: processes are poorly understood. Through analysis of the NCOA4-FTH1 interaction, \n70: we demonstrate that direct association via a key surface arginine in FTH1 and a \n71: C-terminal element in NCOA4 is required for delivery of ferritin to the lysosome \n72: via autophagosomes. Moreover, NCOA4 abundance is under dual control via \n73: autophagy and the ubiquitin proteasome system. Ubiquitin-dependent NCOA4 \n74: turnover is promoted by excess iron and involves an iron-dependent interaction \n75: between NCOA4 and the HERC2 ubiquitin ligase. In zebrafish and cultured cells, \n76: NCOA4 plays an essential role in erythroid differentiation. This work reveals \n77: the molecular nature of the NCOA4-ferritin complex and explains how \n78: intracellular iron levels modulate NCOA4-mediated ferritinophagy in cells and in \n79: an iron-dependent physiological setting.\n80: \n81: DOI: 10.7554/eLife.10308\n82: PMCID: PMC4592949\n83: PMID: 26436293 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n84: \n85: Conflict of interest statement: ACK: reports receiving speakers bureau honoraria \n86: from Agios and the US Oncology Network, and is a consultant for Astellas Pharma, \n87: FORMA Therapeutics, and Gilead. JWH: is a consultant for Millennium: the Takada \n88: Oncology Company and Biogen-Idec. The other authors declare that no competing \n89: interests exist.\n\n(End of file - total 89 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:26436293\ntitle: Ferritinophagy via NCOA4 is required for erythropoiesis and is regulated by iron dependent HERC2-mediated proteolysis.\nauthors:\n- Mancias JD\n- Pontano Vaites L\n- Nissim S\n- Biancur DE\n- Kim AJ\n- Wang X\n- Liu Y\n- Goessling W\n- Kimmelman AC\n- Harper JW\njournal: Elife\nyear: '2015'\ndoi: 10.7554/eLife.10308\nkeywords:\n- Animals\n- Autophagy","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_26436293.md","time":{"start":1778983329138,"end":1778983329185}},"id":"prt_e33ab5d6d0010xRxiZGO9CATWo","sessionID":"ses_1cc5be10bffeihXrzY1FV2TH0l","messageID":"msg_e33ab468a001sFrzEbbjcLiKez"}}
